05820nam a22008415i 9781478021339DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020040898  a97814780213397 a10.1515/97814780213392doi  a(DE-B1597)586303  a(OCoLC)1245588293  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aJV51b.B49 2021 4aJV51b.B49 2021 7aREL1020002bisacsh04a21022300aBeyond Man :bRace, Coloniality, and Philosophy of Religion /ced. by Yountae An, Eleanor Craig. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBlack Outdoors: Innovations in the Poetics of Study : 4600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Challenging Modernity/Coloniality in Philosophy of Religion -- t1 Decolonial Options for a Fragile Secular -- t2 Embodied Counterpoetics -- t3 We Have Never Been Human/e -- t4 The Puritan Atheism of C. L. R. James -- t5 Decolonizing Spectatorship -- t6 The Excremental Sacred -- t7 On Violence and Redemption -- t8 Alter-Carnation -- t9 The Sacred Gone Astray -- t10 Response— On Impassioned Claims -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond Man reimagines the meaning and potential of a philosophy of religion that better attends to the inextricable links among religion, racism, and colonialism. An Yountae, Eleanor Craig, and the contributors reckon with the colonial and racial implications of the field's history by staging a conversation with Black, Indigenous, and decolonial studies. In their introduction, An and Craig point out that European-descended Christianity has historically defined itself by its relation to the other while paradoxically claiming to represent and speak to humanity in its totality. The topics include secularism, the Eucharist's relation to Blackness, and sixteenth-century Brazilian cannibalism rituals as well as an analysis of how Mircea Eliade's conception of the sacred underwrites settler colonial projects and imaginaries. Throughout, the contributors also highlight the theorizing of Afro-Caribbean thinkers such as Sylvia Wynter, C. L. R. James, Frantz Fanon, and Aimé Césaire whose work disrupts the normative Western categories of religion and philosophy.Contributors. An Yountae, Ellen Armour, J. Kameron Carter, Eleanor Craig, Amy Hollywood, Vincent Lloyd, Filipe Maia, Mayra Rivera, Devin Singh, Joseph R. Winters  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivilization, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aCivilization, WesternxChristian influences. 0aDecolonization. 0aEurocentrismxHistory. 0aImperialism. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh1 aAn, Yountae, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmour, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, J. Kameron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Eleanor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHollywood, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaia, Filipe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivera, Mayra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSingh, Devin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinters, Joseph R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYountae, An, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators